Phase 7 #6 — user picks from queued candidates (coverage threshold gate live since Phase 7 #5; TDD mandatory per Rule 25)

Phase 7 #5 shipped on 2026-05-16 as `78fc022`:
- apps/web/vitest.config.ts — added `coverage.thresholds` block: global floor (statements ≥ 12, branches ≥ 6, functions ≥ 12, lines ≥ 12 — matches measured baseline) + per-file gate src/server/trpc/routers/auth.ts (statements 100, branches 75, functions 100, lines 100). Added lcov reporter alongside text + html.
- turbo.json — new `test:coverage` task (dependsOn ^build, outputs coverage/**).
- package.json (root) — new `test:coverage` script delegating to turbo.
- .github/workflows/ci.yml — new `coverage` job (needs: governance, parallel to quality + security) running `pnpm test:coverage` and uploading `apps/web/coverage/` as a 14-day artifact (HTML + lcov) via actions/upload-artifact@v4.
- Gate-engagement verified inline: temporarily bumped auth.ts branches threshold 75 → 99 (above measured 78.94) → confirmed exit 1 with `Coverage for branches (78.94%) does not meet "src/server/trpc/routers/auth.ts" threshold (99%)` → restored to 75.
- 3 new lessons documented: (🔴) nodemailer 6.9.16 still flagged HIGH CVE — three resolution paths queued for candidate (j); (🟤) vitest per-file thresholds via glob keys inside the `thresholds` object; (🟤) PreToolUse workflow-edit warning is precautionary, not diff-aware.
- Visual QA Rule 16 not applicable (no UI changes).

----------------------------------------------------------------------
Candidates (any order, user picks):
----------------------------------------------------------------------

(c) JWT org-slug encoding                   [middleware foundation — high-risk]
    Scope: Tier 3 (~10 files, middleware + auth.config + session callback + all consumers)
    - apps/web/src/server/auth.config.ts — add `organization_slug` to JWT
    - apps/web/src/server/auth.ts — populate from session.user
    - apps/web/src/middleware.ts — resolve tenant from JWT, validate URL ↔ session match (security.md TENANT MIDDLEWARE SAFETY)
    - Test: middleware unit test for tenant-switch attack rejection
    Risk: every authenticated route depends on this; reserve for careful fresh-context session
    Tier 3 → mandatory split via memory-governance §1: probably 3 sub-sessions (auth.config + auth.ts → middleware → consumers).

(d) join/[token] tRPC                       [needs LiveKit ⏳ for full integration]
    Unit tests OK against mocked LiveKit token mint; integration deferred until LIVEKIT_API_KEY filled
    Existing getJoinToken in meetingsRouter has 0 test coverage — could pair with this if scope allows.
    NEW: adding tests for getJoinToken would also let us add a per-file coverage gate on meetings.ts.

(e) Socket.IO auth middleware               [depends on (c)]
    Should land AFTER (c) so the JWT contract is stable.

(f) Root landing page                       [verify scope first]
    Current /page.tsx is 11 lines — check PRODUCT.md for what's expected
    Likely Tier 1.

(h) Tighten request-password-reset rate limiting    [hardening — ~2 files]
    Currently uses rateLimiters.auth (in-memory LRU, ~5/min per IP+key).
    Could add a per-user 24h cap (e.g. ≤5 reset emails per user per day) to prevent
    a targeted user from receiving spam reset emails when an attacker repeatedly
    fires off the endpoint. Cost: another small Prisma query per request.
    Tests would assert the cap engages at request #6 (returns ok still — no enumeration — but
    skips email send + token mint).

(i) Periodic cleanup of expired/consumed password_reset_tokens
    A BullMQ scheduled job to DELETE consumed tokens > 30 days old and unconsumed
    expired tokens > 7 days. Keeps the table from growing unboundedly.
    Pairs naturally with the new coverage gate (g — now shipped) — both are housekeeping.

(j) NEW: Resolve nodemailer HIGH CVE (GHSA-rcmh-qjqh-p98v)    [security — depends on @auth]
    addressparser DoS via recursive calls affects <=7.0.10; we run 6.9.16 pinned for
    Auth.js v5 peer compat. Three documented paths in lessons.md:
      (a) wait for @auth to widen its nodemailer peer range — cleanest, no code changes
      (b) replace nodemailer with a different transport library — touches email.ts + callsites
      (c) document mitigation (server-stamped addresses only, attacker cannot reach the
          vulnerable parser through the password-reset flow) + add `audit-level=critical`
          to .npmrc per phases.md decision tree step 3
    Path (c) is the realistic short-term option; (a) is the long-term hope; (b) is
    last-resort. Decision deserves its own commit + DECISIONS_LOG.md entry.
    Pre-existing on main — not Phase 7 #5 regression but flagged during its audit.

----------------------------------------------------------------------
Rule 25 reminder for ALL of the above:
  → Write failing test FIRST (RED), then implementation (GREEN), then refactor.
  → Test patterns: [[trpc-test-pattern]] (Phase 7 #2) + [[meetings-protected-route-test]] (Phase 7 #3) + [[trpc-test-with-env-mock]] (Phase 7 #4).
  → For forms: reuse the [[shadcn-form-primitive]] pattern from Phase 7 #3 (`_meeting-form.tsx` and `_reset-form.tsx` as reference impls).
  → For shared schemas: `<Entity>CreateClientInputSchema` for client-facing input, `<Entity>CreateInputSchema` for admin/internal projection.
  → For new env vars consumed by routers: add `vi.mock("@/env", ...)` to the test file (extends Phase 7 #4 pattern).
  → NEW (Phase 7 #5): when a router becomes fully tested (>95% across all four metrics), add a per-file threshold to apps/web/vitest.config.ts to lock the new coverage in. Use the [[vitest-per-file-glob-thresholds]] pattern from lessons.md.
  → NEW (Phase 7 #5): coverage thresholds rise organically — add tests → measure → bump threshold. Do NOT lower thresholds to make a regression "fix" pass.

Recommended next: (h) tighten request-password-reset rate limiting — hardening pairs naturally now that the coverage gate locks in the test safety net. Then (c) JWT org-slug middleware (the riskiest open ticket, but unblocks (e) Socket.IO auth). Save (j) for when @auth releases a wider peer range; mitigation analysis is documented in lessons.md regardless.

Pending Rule 16 follow-up: smoke-test /app/meetings/new in browser after next `pnpm dev` up (Phase 7 #3 carryover). ALSO smoke-test /forgot-password + /reset-password/[token] — public routes, no credentials needed (Phase 7 #4 carryover).
